  "answer": "The critic misreads the target. The target’s mechanism claims that Egyptian temple storage was geographically dispersed and redundantly stored across multiple nodal points (Thebes, Memphis, Heliopolis, provincial estates). The forbidden case states that Egyptian temples show concentrated grain storage in New Kingdom administrative papyri. These are not contradictory: administrative papyri can record concentrated storage at individual temple nodes while the overall network remains geographically dispersed and redundant. A single temple’s stores being concentrated on-site does not entail that the system as a whole lacked multiple, geographically separated storage nodes. The forbidden case therefore does not falsify the mechanism’s claim about network-level dispersion and redundancy, and the target is not required to rebut a case that does not actually contradict its asserted mechanism."
